  "prompt": "How many First Ladies have refused to live in the White House?",
  "response": "As of October 2023, **only one First Lady has chosen not to reside in the White House** during her husband's presidency:\n\n### Bess Truman (First Lady from 1945 to 1953)\n\n- **Reason for Not Living in the White House:** \n  - **White House Renovations:** When Harry S. Truman assumed the presidency in April 1945 following Franklin D. Roosevelt's death, the White House was still undergoing significant repairs and renovations. These were necessary due to damage sustained during the 1947 fire and the need to modernize the building.\n  \n- **Alternative Residence:**\n  - **Blair House:** Instead of moving into the White House, Bess Truman and President Truman chose to reside in Blair House, the official guest residence located across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House. This arrangement provided them with a comfortable and private living space while the White House was being prepared for occupancy.\n\n### Additional Context\n\nWhile Bess Truman is the only First Lady known to have permanently declined residence in the White House, there have been instances where First Families temporarily stayed elsewhere due to renovations or other circumstances. However, Bess Truman's decision was unique in that it was a prolonged arrangement spanning the entirety of Truman's presidency.\n\n### Notable Points\n\n- **Historical Significance:** Bess Truman's choice highlighted the practicality and functionality over tradition, ensuring that the president and his family had a suitable living environment during a transitional period for the White House.\n  \n- **Subsequent First Ladies:** Following Bess Truman, all subsequent First Ladies have chosen to reside in the White House, making it a central symbol of the First Family's role in American political life.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nBess Truman remains the only First Lady to have officially refused residence in the White House, opting instead for Blair House due to necessary renovations. This decision underscores a unique moment in White House history and the adaptability of the First Family during times of transition.",
